7. AI Design Engine (Vibe Code Engine)

7.1 Natural Language Design Pipeline
The Vibe Code Engine is the heart of VibeHouse. It accepts natural language input from the user and produces a complete, buildable set of architectural and engineering documents. The pipeline operates in six stages, each producing artifacts that feed into the next.

Stage 1: Vibe Capture
The user describes their desired home through a guided conversational interface. The AI extracts structured requirements from unstructured input using a multi-turn dialogue system. The system captures aesthetic preferences ("I want a warm, modern farmhouse feel"), functional requirements ("4 bedrooms, open kitchen, home office"), site constraints ("0.5 acre lot, gentle slope, south-facing"), budget parameters, and lifestyle needs ("we entertain a lot, need great outdoor living").

Stage 2: Requirement Synthesis
The AI normalizes captured vibes into a structured Requirement Specification Object (RSO) containing room definitions, adjacency preferences, structural constraints, material preferences, code requirements (based on jurisdiction), and budget allocations per system (structural, MEP, finish, landscape).

Stage 3: Floor Plan Generation
Using the RSO, a fine-tuned diffusion model generates multiple floor plan options. Each plan is scored against the requirements using a multi-objective optimization function that weighs spatial efficiency, flow quality, natural light, structural simplicity, and cost. The top 3 plans are presented to the user for selection and refinement.

Stage 4: Engineering Analysis
The selected floor plan is processed through structural, mechanical, electrical, and plumbing analysis engines. Structural loads are calculated, HVAC sizing is determined, electrical panel layouts are generated, and plumbing routes are planned. All calculations conform to the International Building Code (IBC) and local jurisdiction amendments.

Stage 5: Document Generation
Complete construction document sets are generated including architectural plans (floor plans, elevations, sections, details), structural plans (foundation, framing, connections), MEP plans (mechanical, electrical, plumbing), a complete bill of materials with quantities and estimated costs, and a construction schedule with task dependencies and critical path analysis.

Stage 6: Permit Packaging
Documents are formatted to meet local jurisdiction submission requirements, including title block formatting, sheet indexing, energy compliance documentation (Title 24 / IECC), and site plan overlays. The system maintains a database of submission requirements for major U.S. jurisdictions.

