8. Trello Integration & Build Board System

8.1 Build Board Architecture
The Trello Build Board is the operational backbone of every VibeHouse project. It is not a passive Kanban board; it is an AI-monitored, real-time project management surface that every stakeholder interacts with. The AI continuously scans the board for changes, infers intent, updates dependent tasks, and triggers downstream workflows.

Board Structure
Each project generates a Trello board with the following list structure, auto-populated with cards from the construction schedule:

Trello List
Purpose
Card Types
Backlog
All future tasks not yet scheduled
Task cards with dependencies, estimates, assignments
This Week
Tasks scheduled for the current week
Active task cards with daily breakdowns
In Progress
Tasks currently being worked on
Cards moved here by contractors or AI
Blocked
Tasks that cannot proceed
Cards with blocker annotations, auto-escalation timers
In Review / Inspection
Tasks awaiting quality check or inspection
Cards with inspection checklists, photo requirements
Dispute / Hold
Tasks with active disputes or holds
Cards linked to dispute resolution workflows
Completed
Tasks verified as complete
Cards with completion evidence, sign-off records
Change Orders
Scope changes requested or approved
Cards with cost impact, approval status, timeline impact

8.2 AI Board Scanning Engine
The Trello Sync Service continuously monitors the Build Board using a combination of Trello webhooks (for real-time push notifications) and periodic polling (as a reliability fallback). The scanning engine processes the following event types:

	•	Card Moves: When a card is moved between lists, the AI evaluates whether the move is valid (does the task have unresolved dependencies?), updates dependent task timelines, triggers notifications to affected stakeholders, and recalculates the critical path.
	•	Card Comments: Natural language comments from contractors or the homeowner are parsed by the AI. Comments indicating problems ("concrete delivery delayed 2 days") trigger automatic schedule adjustments. Questions ("can we substitute oak for maple?") are routed to the appropriate decision-maker.
	•	Checklist Updates: Inspection checklists and task completion checklists are monitored. When all items are checked, the AI auto-advances the card to the next stage or flags items that need manual verification.
	•	Label Changes: Color-coded labels indicate priority, risk level, and category. The AI monitors label changes and adjusts reporting and escalation behavior accordingly.
	•	Due Date Modifications: Any due date change triggers a cascading dependency analysis. The AI identifies all downstream tasks affected, calculates new projected dates, and generates a schedule impact report.

8.3 Webhook Processing Pipeline

Step
Action
Latency Target
1. Receive
Trello webhook hits /api/v1/webhooks/trello endpoint
< 100ms ACK
2. Validate
Verify webhook signature, parse payload, deduplicate
< 50ms
3. Classify
Determine event type and affected entities
< 100ms
4. Enqueue
Push to appropriate Celery task queue with priority
< 50ms
5. Process
Execute business logic, update internal state
< 2s
6. Cascade
Trigger dependent updates, notifications, reports
< 5s
7. Sync Back
Push any AI-generated changes back to Trello
< 3s

8.4 Board Sync Reliability
To ensure the Trello board and the VibeHouse internal state never diverge, the system implements a three-tier consistency model: real-time webhook processing as the primary sync mechanism, a 60-second polling interval as a secondary fallback that catches any missed webhooks, and a full board reconciliation job that runs every 15 minutes comparing the complete Trello board state against the internal database and resolving any discrepancies.

9. Vendor & Contractor Orchestration

9.1 Vendor Discovery Pipeline
When the construction schedule is finalized, the Orchestration Service automatically identifies the trades required for each phase and begins the vendor discovery and engagement process. The pipeline operates as follows:

	1	Trade Identification: Parse the construction schedule to identify all required trades (e.g., concrete, framing, electrical, plumbing, HVAC, roofing, drywall, painting, flooring, landscaping).
	2	Geographic Search: Query the vendor database and external APIs (Google Places, Yelp, state licensing boards) for licensed contractors within a configurable radius of the build site.
	3	Qualification Filtering: Filter results by license status, insurance coverage, bond status, years in business, online rating thresholds, and any homeowner-specified preferences.
	4	Availability Matching: Cross-reference contractor availability calendars against the project schedule to identify contractors who can meet the required start dates.
	5	AI Ranking: Score qualified contractors using a composite algorithm weighing price history, quality ratings, reliability scores, proximity, past VibeHouse performance, and schedule fit.
	6	Automated Outreach: Send personalized RFQ (Request for Quotation) packages to the top-ranked contractors via email and SMS, including project scope, timeline, plans, and a response portal link.
	7	Bid Collection & Comparison: Aggregate incoming bids, normalize pricing structures, and present a comparison matrix to the homeowner with AI recommendations.
	8	Contract Generation: Upon selection, auto-generate scope-specific contracts with payment milestones tied to Trello card completion.

9.2 Outreach Communication Templates
All vendor communications are generated by the AI and customized per trade, project, and contractor. Templates include initial RFQ emails, follow-up reminders (3-day and 7-day), bid acceptance notifications, contract packages, onboarding instructions with Trello board access, and schedule confirmation messages. Each communication is logged in the project audit trail and linked to the corresponding Trello card.

