12.2 Application Structure
The backend follows a modular monolith pattern deployed as containerized microservices. Each service domain has its own Python package within a monorepo, sharing common libraries for authentication, database access, and messaging.

Project Layout
vibehouse/
	•	api/ - FastAPI application, route handlers, middleware, WebSocket endpoints
	•	core/ - Domain models, business logic, service layer
	◦	core/vibe_engine/ - AI design pipeline, model interfaces, plan generation
	◦	core/orchestration/ - Vendor discovery, outreach, bid management
	◦	core/trello_sync/ - Board management, webhook handlers, scan engine
	◦	core/reporting/ - Report generation, analytics, notification dispatch
	◦	core/disputes/ - Conflict detection, resolution workflows, mediation
	•	db/ - SQLAlchemy models, Alembic migrations, query helpers
	•	tasks/ - Celery task definitions, schedules, retry policies
	•	integrations/ - Third-party API clients (Trello, Twilio, SendGrid, Stripe)
	•	common/ - Shared utilities, logging, error handling, constants
	•	tests/ - Unit, integration, and end-to-end test suites

12.3 Async Architecture
The entire backend is async-first. All I/O-bound operations use Python asyncio with async database drivers (asyncpg), async HTTP clients (httpx), and async Redis connections (redis.asyncio). CPU-bound operations like AI model inference and document generation are offloaded to Celery workers running in separate containers, preventing the API servers from blocking.

