15. Security & Compliance

15.1 Authentication & Authorization
	•	OAuth 2.0 + JWT: All API access requires valid JWT tokens issued via OAuth 2.0 authorization code flow. Tokens expire after 1 hour with refresh token rotation.
	•	Role-Based Access Control (RBAC): Four roles: Homeowner, Contractor, Inspector, Admin. Each role has granular permissions mapped to API endpoints and data visibility.
	•	Multi-Factor Authentication: Required for all financial operations, contract signing, and dispute escalation actions.
	•	API Key Management: Service-to-service communication uses rotated API keys with IP whitelisting.

15.2 Data Protection
	•	Encryption at Rest: AES-256 encryption for all data in PostgreSQL (pgcrypto), S3 (SSE-S3), and Redis (TLS).
	•	Encryption in Transit: TLS 1.3 enforced on all connections. Certificate pinning for mobile clients.
	•	PII Handling: Personal information is stored in dedicated encrypted columns with access logging. Contractor SSN/EIN data is tokenized via Stripe Identity.
	•	Audit Logging: Every data access, modification, and API call is logged with actor, timestamp, IP, and before/after state diffs.

15.3 Compliance
	•	SOC 2 Type II: Targeted for Phase 2 certification. Controls implemented from Phase 1.
	•	CCPA/GDPR: Full data portability, deletion rights, consent management, and privacy dashboard.
	•	PCI DSS: Payment processing delegated to Stripe. No raw card data touches VibeHouse servers.
	•	Construction Licensing: Platform verifies contractor licenses against state databases before engagement.

16. Performance & Scalability

16.1 Scaling Strategy
VibeHouse is designed to scale horizontally at every layer. API servers are stateless and scale behind a load balancer. Celery workers scale independently per queue priority. PostgreSQL uses read replicas for reporting queries and connection pooling via PgBouncer. Redis Cluster provides distributed caching with automatic sharding.

